For example, `MultiKey("A", "B")` would have the same hash code as `MultiKey("B", "A")` since XOR is commutative.

Looking at the `equals` method:

```java
@Override
public boolean equals(final Object other) {
    if (other == this) {
        return true;
    }
    if (other instanceof MultiKey) {
        final MultiKey<?> otherMulti = (MultiKey<?>) other;
        return Arrays.equals(keys, otherMulti.keys);
    }
    return false;
}
```

This uses `Arrays.equals` which DOES care about the order of elements. So if `MultiKey("A", "B")` and `MultiKey("B", "A")` have the same hash code but are considered not equal by `equals`, it violates the hash code contract!

This is likely the bug! The hash code calculation doesn't preserve element ordering, but `Arrays.equals` does. This would cause hash inconsistencies, and in the case of serialization/deserialization of derived classes, there might be some subtle ordering differences or other internal state differences that expose this bug.

